<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-9-30">
  <title>Resources for 9/30</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Explain and use the definition of <em>inverse functions</em>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given the formula for a function <m>f</m>, determine the formula for the inverse function <m>f^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given the graph of a function <m>f</m>, determine whether or not the inverse function <m>f^{-1}</m> exists.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-intro-inverse-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Introduction to Inverse Functions (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video introducing <em>inverse functions</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="px0-Wo2QVrk" />

    <problem>
      <title>Introduction to Inverse Functions</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following introductory inverse function problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              If possible, find the inverse for each of the following functions.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>f(x)=5x-6</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>f(x) = 3x^3+11</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Define the functions <m>f: \{ -3,-1,1,2,3,5 \} \rightarrow \{3,7,9,10 \}</m> and <m>g: \{ 1,2,4,5,6,10 \} \rightarrow \{ -3,1,2,3,5,7 \}</m> by 
              <md>f = \{(1,3),(5,7),(2,3),(3,9),(-1,7),(-3,10)\},</md>
              <md>g=\{(5,2),(1,3),(4,1),(6,-3),(2,7),(10,5)\}</md>
        Note that for each function, the first coordinate of each ordered pair is the input and the second is the output.  Find <m>f^{-1}</m> and/or <m>g^{-1}</m>, if possible.  In other words, try to find functions that cancel <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, respectively.  Determine the domain and range of the inverse function(s).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the inverse, if possible, for <m>f(x)=x^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-advanced-inverse">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Determining Inverse Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on some more advanced techniques for <em>determining inverse functions</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="wDAUo4rEzFU" />

    <problem>
      <title>Advanced Inverse Functions</title>
      <p>
        For each of the following, compute <m>f^{-1}(x)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=x^3-1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=\frac{2x+1}{3x+4}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Optional Reading</title>
    <p>
      Section 1.7: pp. 72-80
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a link for the <url href="https://activecalculus.org/prelude/sec-changing-inverse.html">HTML version of Section 1.7</url>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>